{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "Conventionally used in materials characterization facilities, SEM imaging has become increasingly accessible with the advent of low-cost bench top systems.",
    "SEM generates high-resolution visuals of sample surfaces (Tafti et al. 2015), excelling in nanoscale structure visualization (Kelsall et al. 2005).",
    "Despite its advantages, SEM necessitates a vacuum setting and extensive sample preparation, potentially extending the preparatory duration, though the latter is less of a factor in environmental SEM imaging mode.",
    "Within the context of integration within DL frameworks, SEM's high spatial resolution furnish valuable data, particularly for studies of microfossil assemblages, though the grayscale nature of native SEM images does restrict their data richness, with limited signal contrast from the mapped surfaces of many specimens being deleterious towards the performance of DL models in tasks such as segmentation (Saif et al. 2017).",
    "Infrared imaging utilizes infrared light to illuminate a sample, which then absorbs or reflects the light."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "SEM generates high-resolution visuals of sample surfaces (Tafti et al. 2015), excelling in nanoscale structure visualization (Kelsall et al. 2005).",
    "Within the context of integration within DL frameworks, SEM's high spatial resolution furnish valuable data, particularly for studies of microfossil assemblages, though the grayscale nature of native SEM images does restrict their data richness, with limited signal contrast from the mapped surfaces of many specimens being deleterious towards the performance of DL models in tasks such as segmentation (Saif et al. 2017)."
